f Shari’ah and Common Law: Findings and Recommendations -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHarmonisation of law, a term that refers to the bringing together of two different legal traditions, has developed a negative connotation when considered in the context of Shari’ah and common law. Harmonisation began to be looked at as an attempt by one legal system to impose its values on the other. A major reason for that is the lack of understanding of the scope to which these two legal traditions converge. One of the principal findings of this book is that Shari’ah and common law have many more commonalities than differences. As a result, the need for harmonisation between the two might have been exaggerated. The similarities do not need to be harmonised. Rather, they need to be acknowledged and appreciated. If the differences between Shari’ah and common law, which undoubtedly exist as evidenced in this book, are viewed with an appreciation of the commonalities, the ambiance to reconcile the differences would be more conducive to the harmonisation process. This book is intended to help readers better understand Shari’ah and common law and aid harmonisation efforts when the need arises.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aGewohnheitsrecht. 4aRecht in Asien. 4aSharia. 4aVergleichendes Recht. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Business Law.2bisacsh  aShari’ah and Common Law, Harmonisation of Law, Comparative Law, Law in Asia, Law and Society.1 aTrakic, Adnan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z97831107668200 cEPUBz97831107667140 cprintz978311076668440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311076670740uhtt